WEBVTT

﻿1
00:00:05.701 --> 00:00:07.397
<i>In the criminal justice system.</i>

2
00:00:07.398 --> 00:00:08.790
<i>the people are represented</i>

3
00:00:08.791 --> 00:00:11.011
<i>by two separate.
yet equally important groups:</i>

4
00:00:11.185 --> 00:00:13.013
<i>the police. who investigate crime.</i>

5
00:00:13.230 --> 00:00:15.884
<i>and the district attorneys.
who prosecute the offenders.</i>

6
00:00:15.885 --> 00:00:17.713
<i>These are their stories.</i>

7
00:00:19.019 --> 00:00:21.630
[LIVELY CHATTER]

8
00:00:21.847 --> 00:00:23.047
[UP-TEMPO PIANO MUSIC PLAYING]

9
00:00:23.240 --> 00:00:24.763
[SIGHS] 24.

10
00:00:24.981 --> 00:00:27.766
Tough luck.

11
00:00:27.984 --> 00:00:29.812
Son of a bitch!

12
00:00:30.030 --> 00:00:31.465
You're killing me.

13
00:00:31.466 --> 00:00:33.386
What are you doing.
hitting the 16 against a 5?

14
00:00:33.468 --> 00:00:34.556
It's suicide.

15
00:00:34.773 --> 00:00:36.906
I do it my way.

16
00:00:37.080 --> 00:00:38.690
Hey.

17
00:00:38.908 --> 00:00:41.389
Take it easy. okay?

18
00:00:41.606 --> 00:00:45.392
Your marker to cover this
last shoe didn't go through.

19
00:00:45.393 --> 00:00:48.352
That's impossible. bro.

20
00:00:48.570 --> 00:00:51.007
I need you two to come with me.

21
00:00:51.181 --> 00:00:53.314
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22
00:00:53.531 --> 00:00:55.185
Leave the chips.

23
00:00:57.000 --> 00:01:03.074
Support us and become VIP member 
to remove all ads from www.OpenSubtitles.org

24
00:01:04.977 --> 00:01:06.327
Your guy's late.

25
00:01:06.544 --> 00:01:07.676
<i>[TENSE MUSIC]</i>

26
00:01:07.893 --> 00:01:09.460
He's coming.

27
00:01:09.678 --> 00:01:11.810
I promise.

28
00:01:12.028 --> 00:01:16.250
See. when you hand over
a credit card to pay for cards.

29
00:01:16.467 --> 00:01:18.861
that's a promise. too. right?

30
00:01:19.079 --> 00:01:22.038
So your word doesn't mean
a whole lot around here

31
00:01:22.212 --> 00:01:24.040
right now. you understand?

32
00:01:27.087 --> 00:01:29.437
What are you two doing here anyway?

33
00:01:29.654 --> 00:01:31.395
You're out there for months at a time.

34
00:01:31.613 --> 00:01:34.572
You have 48 hours in the city.
You wind up in here.

35
00:01:34.790 --> 00:01:37.400
playing cards you suck at
and can't afford.

36
00:01:37.401 --> 00:01:38.794
I don't know.

37
00:01:39.011 --> 00:01:42.319
[DOOR CLICKS]

38
00:01:43.364 --> 00:01:44.843
Oh. good.

39
00:01:45.061 --> 00:01:47.107
Daddy's here.

40
00:01:47.281 --> 00:01:53.287
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41
00:01:53.504 --> 00:01:55.158
Let's get this done.

42
00:01:55.376 --> 00:01:56.812
Four grand.

43
00:01:57.029 --> 00:01:58.901
Make it six.

44
00:02:00.859 --> 00:02:04.646
It's a little motto
I learned in business school.

45
00:02:04.863 --> 00:02:08.911
Where there's four. there is six.

46
00:02:09.129 --> 00:02:11.609
<i>♪ ♪</i>

47
00:02:11.827 --> 00:02:14.699
Then we have two choices.

48
00:02:14.917 --> 00:02:16.832
Educate me. please.

49
00:02:17.049 --> 00:02:20.052
I give you the four grand
that they owe you.

50
00:02:20.227 --> 00:02:22.707
or you're gonna ask me for six again.

51
00:02:22.925 --> 00:02:25.493
and when you do.

52
00:02:25.710 --> 00:02:28.931
make sure you got those guys
by your side.

53
00:02:29.149 --> 00:02:36.112
<i>♪ ♪</i>

54
00:02:37.374 --> 00:02:39.419
[CAMERA SHUTTER SNAPPING]

55
00:02:39.420 --> 00:02:42.945
[SIRENS WHOOPING]

56
00:02:43.163 --> 00:02:45.208
Okay. Officer. what do we got?

57
00:02:45.426 --> 00:02:47.210
It happened up there.

58
00:02:47.428 --> 00:02:49.473
No way he's surviving that.

59
00:02:49.691 --> 00:02:51.214
We're sure he didn't fall?

60
00:02:51.432 --> 00:02:52.607
Or jump?

61
00:02:52.824 --> 00:02:54.150
'Cause that's a different department.

62
00:02:54.174 --> 00:02:56.828
No. he was pushed.

63
00:02:57.046 --> 00:02:58.265
That lady called 911.

64
00:02:58.482 --> 00:03:01.659
At 10:35. she was walking down here.

65
00:03:01.877 --> 00:03:03.444
heard arguing between two men.

66
00:03:03.661 --> 00:03:06.186
Next thing she knew.
this guy went over the side.

67
00:03:06.360 --> 00:03:08.362
screaming. grabbing at the air.

68
00:03:08.579 --> 00:03:10.102
Cracked his head open.

69
00:03:10.277 --> 00:03:12.061
Hey.

70
00:03:12.121 --> 00:03:13.192
Hey. what are you doing here. Lou?

71
00:03:13.193 --> 00:03:15.456
Victim's name is Wally Kane.

72
00:03:15.673 --> 00:03:18.110
He's a vice admiral in the U.S. Navy.

73
00:03:18.285 --> 00:03:20.765
commander of a strike group
visiting for Fleet Week.

74
00:03:20.983 --> 00:03:22.375
Everybody's watching this one...

75
00:03:22.376 --> 00:03:24.813
- [PHONE BUZZES]
- Including the DA.

76
00:03:27.032 --> 00:03:28.860
Damn.

77
00:03:30.732 --> 00:03:33.864
<i>[DRAMATIC MUSIC]</i>

78
00:03:33.865 --> 00:03:40.959
<i>♪ ♪</i>

79
00:04:16.560 --> 00:04:19.346
<i>Why was Wally Kane in New York. huh?</i>

80
00:04:19.563 --> 00:04:24.089
<i>For Fleet Week. a celebration
of America's maritime power.</i>

81
00:04:24.264 --> 00:04:26.962
<i>That's who New York City
managed to fail this time.</i>

82
00:04:27.179 --> 00:04:28.789
<i>our very best.</i>

83
00:04:28.790 --> 00:04:30.182
<i>Why? Look right to the top.</i>

84
00:04:30.357 --> 00:04:33.098
<i>to the weak. soft-on-crime DA.</i>

85
00:04:33.273 --> 00:04:34.404
<i>This city is overrun...</i>

86
00:04:34.622 --> 00:04:36.145
No worse enemy than a former friend.

87
00:04:36.319 --> 00:04:38.079
<i>- They can't even protect...</i>
- [TV SWITCHES OFF]

88
00:04:38.103 --> 00:04:40.541
Well. I already contributed
to your campaign. so...

89
00:04:40.758 --> 00:04:42.455
Thanks for stopping by.

90
00:04:42.456 --> 00:04:44.816
The death of Vice Admiral Kane
has already gotten political.

91
00:04:44.849 --> 00:04:45.849
It's only been 12 hours.

92
00:04:45.981 --> 00:04:47.329
Political how?

93
00:04:47.330 --> 00:04:50.115
Well. it turns out
that the soft-on-crime DA

94
00:04:50.290 --> 00:04:51.768
is to blame for all this.

95
00:04:51.769 --> 00:04:53.660
- Okay. so you need answers.
- As soon as possible.

96
00:04:53.684 --> 00:04:54.771
We're on it.

97
00:04:54.772 --> 00:04:57.253
Nick. doors open in five minutes.

98
00:04:57.427 --> 00:04:59.255
Just stay on message
to the extent possible.

99
00:04:59.429 --> 00:05:01.170
and just be charming.

100
00:05:01.344 --> 00:05:02.824
It's what I do.

101
00:05:03.041 --> 00:05:04.521
Gotta go. Keep me updated. OK?

102
00:05:04.739 --> 00:05:05.957
Good luck.

103
00:05:07.916 --> 00:05:10.484
[INDISTINCT SPEECH]

104
00:05:10.701 --> 00:05:15.662
Wally Kane carried out
airstrikes in Bosnia.

105
00:05:15.663 --> 00:05:19.971
flew sorties in Kosovo.

106
00:05:20.189 --> 00:05:23.235
coordinated strikes
against the Taliban.

107
00:05:23.410 --> 00:05:27.065
We've become generous
with the word "hero."

108
00:05:27.283 --> 00:05:31.331
But out there.
character reveals itself

109
00:05:31.505 --> 00:05:35.509
in ways land rats can't understand.

110
00:05:35.726 --> 00:05:39.469
If there was risk. he faced it.

111
00:05:39.687 --> 00:05:43.778
Consequence... he absorbed it.

112
00:05:43.995 --> 00:05:46.214
Recognition or praise...

113
00:05:46.215 --> 00:05:48.435
well. he passed that on to you.

114
00:05:48.652 --> 00:05:53.657
Honor him by obeying his wishes.

115
00:05:53.875 --> 00:05:57.095
Take care of your shipmates.

116
00:05:57.313 --> 00:05:58.445
We have the watch.

117
00:05:58.662 --> 00:06:00.447
ALL: Aye. aye. sir!

118
00:06:02.971 --> 00:06:08.150
Wally Kane and I were friends
for 30 years.

119
00:06:08.368 --> 00:06:10.457
Sounds like he meant
a lot to this crew.

120
00:06:10.674 --> 00:06:13.242
We understand he spent
most of his time on this ship.

121
00:06:13.416 --> 00:06:14.547
Uh-huh.

122
00:06:14.548 --> 00:06:18.029
He... he loved the job. the mission.

123
00:06:18.247 --> 00:06:20.945
Right. Were you with him last night?

124
00:06:21.163 --> 00:06:22.511
No.

125
00:06:22.512 --> 00:06:24.232
When we're here for Fleet Week.
I'm slammed.

126
00:06:24.384 --> 00:06:27.299
Part of the routine is we open
up the fleet to the public.

127
00:06:27.474 --> 00:06:28.518
show off what we do.

128
00:06:28.736 --> 00:06:30.477
So I was stuck here on the ship.

129
00:06:30.694 --> 00:06:32.494
Did Vice Admiral Kane
seem like he was under

130
00:06:32.609 --> 00:06:34.089
any strain lately?

131
00:06:34.306 --> 00:06:35.612
Anything seem off?

132
00:06:35.830 --> 00:06:38.223
No. If anything. he was on a high.

133
00:06:38.398 --> 00:06:40.038
You may have read that
I've been nominated

134
00:06:40.182 --> 00:06:41.662
to be the next Secretary of Defense.

135
00:06:41.879 --> 00:06:45.361
which meant that Wally
was in line to take my job.

136
00:06:45.535 --> 00:06:47.972
getting his fourth star.

137
00:06:48.190 --> 00:06:50.453
We got access to Vice Admiral
Kane's credit cards.

138
00:06:50.671 --> 00:06:53.456
and it looks like he took out
a $4.000 cash advance

139
00:06:53.674 --> 00:06:55.762
last night downtown on Orchard Street.

140
00:06:55.763 --> 00:06:57.923
Any idea why he might have
been in that part of town?

141
00:06:57.982 --> 00:06:59.506
No. Sorry.

142
00:06:59.723 --> 00:07:00.985
- Excuse me. sir.
- Yeah.

143
00:07:03.988 --> 00:07:05.708
Admiral. Seaman Harris
and Seaman Nicholls

144
00:07:05.903 --> 00:07:07.446
request permission
to speak with the officers.

145
00:07:07.470 --> 00:07:10.299
Detectives.

146
00:07:10.473 --> 00:07:12.214
Carry on.

147
00:07:15.043 --> 00:07:18.481
We have something we need to confess.

148
00:07:18.699 --> 00:07:20.135
Wally Kane paid their tab?

149
00:07:20.352 --> 00:07:21.982
Yeah. apparently.
these two dopey sailors

150
00:07:22.006 --> 00:07:24.355
got way in over their head
playing blackjack.

151
00:07:24.356 --> 00:07:26.533
Kane shows up with four grand
to bail them out.

152
00:07:26.750 --> 00:07:28.186
That's a hell of a boss.

153
00:07:28.404 --> 00:07:29.816
You'd do the same thing for me. right?

154
00:07:29.840 --> 00:07:31.233
No. I definitely would not.

155
00:07:31.451 --> 00:07:33.148
We're putting together
a timeline here.

156
00:07:33.365 --> 00:07:35.672
Looks like Kane left
the card room around 9:30 p.m..

157
00:07:35.890 --> 00:07:37.500
assuming he was going back
to the ship.

158
00:07:37.718 --> 00:07:39.240
An elevated walkway would
have been a good way to go.

159
00:07:39.241 --> 00:07:40.459
Until it wasn't.

160
00:07:40.460 --> 00:07:42.505
Hey. check this out.

161
00:07:42.723 --> 00:07:44.028
Just got footage of the incident

162
00:07:44.246 --> 00:07:45.987
from this little bodega
across the street.

163
00:07:46.204 --> 00:07:47.902
- Of the actual crime?
- Mm-hmm.

164
00:07:48.119 --> 00:07:49.555
I mean. the quality's not great.

165
00:07:49.556 --> 00:07:52.167
but if you step through it.
it tells the story.

166
00:07:52.384 --> 00:07:53.473
There's Kane.

167
00:07:55.475 --> 00:07:56.563
Here comes another guy.

168
00:07:56.780 --> 00:07:58.220
I can't quite make out his features.

169
00:08:00.480 --> 00:08:01.568
They argue.

170
00:08:01.785 --> 00:08:03.787
It gets nasty quick.

171
00:08:04.005 --> 00:08:05.572
And then...

172
00:08:05.789 --> 00:08:07.878
- [EXHALES]
- Man. what a way to go.

173
00:08:08.096 --> 00:08:10.664
Yeah. we lose the perp after that.

174
00:08:10.881 --> 00:08:12.142
The warrant landed.

175
00:08:12.143 --> 00:08:13.971
We just got access
to Kane's text messages.

176
00:08:14.189 --> 00:08:15.406
And?

177
00:08:15.407 --> 00:08:17.366
"You owe me. Alternative bad for all."

178
00:08:17.540 --> 00:08:18.759
9:40 p.m. last night.

179
00:08:18.976 --> 00:08:21.326
9:40 p.m.

180
00:08:21.501 --> 00:08:23.503
Kane was dead an hour later.

181
00:08:23.677 --> 00:08:25.287
- Who sent that?
- I don't know yet.

182
00:08:25.505 --> 00:08:27.419
The contact name
on the phone is just FM.

183
00:08:27.594 --> 00:08:28.812
Okay.

184
00:08:29.030 --> 00:08:30.597
Let's figure it out and find him.

185
00:08:31.946 --> 00:08:34.078
"Alternative bad for all."

186
00:08:34.296 --> 00:08:36.907
I'm no genius. Mr. Mazzeo.
but it feels like

187
00:08:37.125 --> 00:08:39.519
the alternative
in this case was murder.

188
00:08:39.693 --> 00:08:43.131
No. it was... I was...

189
00:08:43.348 --> 00:08:45.481
Wally and I have known
each other forever.

190
00:08:45.655 --> 00:08:46.655
It was a little dispute.

191
00:08:46.700 --> 00:08:47.700
Dispute about what?

192
00:08:47.744 --> 00:08:49.137
Business.

193
00:08:49.354 --> 00:08:50.877
Wally Kane was in the Navy.

194
00:08:50.878 --> 00:08:53.576
We were talking about
investing in a new venture.

195
00:08:53.794 --> 00:08:56.492
I own and lease ports
all over the country.

196
00:08:56.666 --> 00:08:58.842
So his skill set was useful to me.

197
00:08:59.060 --> 00:09:01.932
Well. when was the last time
you saw Vice Admiral Kane?

198
00:09:02.150 --> 00:09:03.891
I don't know.

199
00:09:04.108 --> 00:09:05.240
A few months?

200
00:09:05.457 --> 00:09:07.547
Hmm.

201
00:09:07.764 --> 00:09:11.028
Frank. we tracked his Fitbit.

202
00:09:11.246 --> 00:09:14.204
We know you were with him last night

203
00:09:14.205 --> 00:09:16.164
at Bub O'Malley's bar. 8:30 p.m.

204
00:09:16.381 --> 00:09:18.514
It's really not a good look.

205
00:09:18.688 --> 00:09:20.951
- It's not what you think.
- No?

206
00:09:21.169 --> 00:09:22.997
'Cause it seems pretty simple to me.

207
00:09:23.214 --> 00:09:24.388
Wally owed you money.

208
00:09:24.389 --> 00:09:25.826
You tried to resolve it at the bar.

209
00:09:26.043 --> 00:09:27.697
It didn't work out.
so you hunted him down

210
00:09:27.915 --> 00:09:29.177
on the elevated walkway.

211
00:09:29.394 --> 00:09:30.754
and then you pushed him overboard.

212
00:09:30.787 --> 00:09:32.572
- No.
- No?

213
00:09:32.789 --> 00:09:35.139
That's not... we met up
to talk about business.

214
00:09:35.357 --> 00:09:38.969
and then I went home. I swear.
and I can prove it to you.

215
00:09:39.187 --> 00:09:40.623
- [KNOCK AT DOOR]
- [DOOR OPENS]

216
00:09:40.841 --> 00:09:42.756
Hey. Lou. I need you
out here a minute.

217
00:09:42.973 --> 00:09:44.148
Now?

218
00:09:44.366 --> 00:09:45.976
ADIC's here.

219
00:09:46.194 --> 00:09:47.498
Who is here?

220
00:09:47.499 --> 00:09:49.719
Assistant Director
In Charge of the FBI.

221
00:09:49.937 --> 00:09:52.592
<i>[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC]</i>

222
00:09:52.809 --> 00:09:59.599
<i>♪ ♪</i>

223
00:10:00.556 --> 00:10:02.079
You need to release Frank Mazzeo.

224
00:10:02.297 --> 00:10:03.646
Why is that?

225
00:10:03.864 --> 00:10:05.692
I can't get into the details
at the moment.

226
00:10:05.909 --> 00:10:07.709
Well. we're investigating
him for the murder

227
00:10:07.737 --> 00:10:09.390
of a vice admiral
in the United States Navy.

228
00:10:09.391 --> 00:10:11.611
He didn't do it. I assure you.

229
00:10:11.828 --> 00:10:13.569
Okay. Well. then. forget it.

230
00:10:13.743 --> 00:10:15.702
I can explain more later.
but right now. I...

231
00:10:15.919 --> 00:10:17.616
What's his alibi?

232
00:10:17.617 --> 00:10:19.595
I mean. do you have any proof
for us that he's not involved?

233
00:10:19.619 --> 00:10:22.230
Like I said. we can talk
about all this down the road.

234
00:10:22.447 --> 00:10:25.146
but right now.
we need to pull him out.

235
00:10:25.363 --> 00:10:26.581
I'm not releasing him.

236
00:10:26.582 --> 00:10:28.540
Then that would be a bad career move.

237
00:10:28.715 --> 00:10:30.891
Are you seriously threatening me?

238
00:10:31.108 --> 00:10:32.632
All right. Jess. come on.

239
00:10:32.849 --> 00:10:34.677
We just need to know that
Mr. Mazzeo is not

240
00:10:34.895 --> 00:10:37.724
gonna be leaving town anytime soon.

241
00:10:37.941 --> 00:10:38.942
He's not.

242
00:10:39.160 --> 00:10:43.730
<i>♪ ♪</i>

243
00:10:43.947 --> 00:10:45.166
Fine. he's all yours.

244
00:10:45.383 --> 00:10:52.042
<i>♪ ♪</i>

245
00:10:52.869 --> 00:10:54.915
Time to go.

246
00:10:55.132 --> 00:11:02.052
<i>♪ ♪</i>

247
00:11:08.058 --> 00:11:09.625
What the hell is going on?

248
00:11:09.799 --> 00:11:11.975
<i>♪ ♪</i>

249
00:11:17.546 --> 00:11:18.678
Thank you.

250
00:11:18.852 --> 00:11:20.070
Frank Mazzeo's alibi holds up.

251
00:11:20.288 --> 00:11:21.808
He was home at the time of the murder.

252
00:11:21.898 --> 00:11:23.746
But he admits talking
business with Wally Kane

253
00:11:23.770 --> 00:11:25.597
and then sending him
a nasty text afterward.

254
00:11:25.772 --> 00:11:27.295
And apparently. he's so important

255
00:11:27.512 --> 00:11:28.881
that the FBI can just
rip him out of the middle

256
00:11:28.905 --> 00:11:30.428
of an interrogation.

257
00:11:30.646 --> 00:11:32.102
Well. just because Mazzeo
didn't commit the murder

258
00:11:32.126 --> 00:11:33.867
doesn't mean
he's not involved somehow.

259
00:11:34.084 --> 00:11:36.062
Let's track his movements
from the time he left the bar

260
00:11:36.086 --> 00:11:38.393
at 8:30 until the 911 call.

261
00:11:41.483 --> 00:11:45.792
Mr. Campisi.
is that your vehicle. sir?

262
00:11:46.009 --> 00:11:49.621
- That's my vehicle.
- So you know Frank Mazzeo.

263
00:11:49.796 --> 00:11:51.711
- I do.
- How?

264
00:11:51.928 --> 00:11:53.451
We work together.

265
00:11:53.669 --> 00:11:55.715
You own and lease ports too?

266
00:11:55.932 --> 00:11:57.238
No.

267
00:11:57.455 --> 00:12:00.589
I work for the FBI.

268
00:12:00.763 --> 00:12:02.634
So Mazzeo was working undercover?

269
00:12:02.809 --> 00:12:04.985
No. He's an informant.

270
00:12:05.202 --> 00:12:06.943
And you're his handler?

271
00:12:07.161 --> 00:12:09.226
That's why I was over
at Bub O'Malley's that night.

272
00:12:09.250 --> 00:12:11.600
Was Wally Kane involved in this?

273
00:12:11.774 --> 00:12:13.733
Look. we're on the same team.

274
00:12:13.907 --> 00:12:15.430
I get it.

275
00:12:15.647 --> 00:12:18.563
But this needs to stay off the record.

276
00:12:18.738 --> 00:12:20.348
You got it.

277
00:12:20.565 --> 00:12:24.178
Wally Kane was our target.

278
00:12:24.395 --> 00:12:25.745
Can you be more specific?

279
00:12:28.051 --> 00:12:29.748
Look. we don't need
chapter and verse here.

280
00:12:29.749 --> 00:12:31.422
We just wanna know if
your operation has anything

281
00:12:31.446 --> 00:12:32.446
to do with our murder.

282
00:12:32.534 --> 00:12:33.970
I don't know.

283
00:12:34.188 --> 00:12:36.233
- Sorry.
- What kind of case is it?

284
00:12:36.451 --> 00:12:38.583
Bribery.

285
00:12:38.758 --> 00:12:41.630
Mazzeo controls a big chunk
of the waterfront around here.

286
00:12:41.804 --> 00:12:43.110
And he was paying people off

287
00:12:43.327 --> 00:12:45.329
so they would dock
their boats in his ports.

288
00:12:45.547 --> 00:12:48.376
And Wally Kane was
one of those people?

289
00:12:48.593 --> 00:12:50.944
So he's taking bribes
to dock Navy vessels

290
00:12:51.161 --> 00:12:52.641
with this Mazzeo guy. huh?

291
00:12:52.815 --> 00:12:54.774
Yes.

292
00:12:54.991 --> 00:12:55.991
Anyone else involved?

293
00:12:56.123 --> 00:12:58.908
<i>[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC]</i>

294
00:12:59.126 --> 00:13:00.387
What is your business
with the admiral?

295
00:13:00.388 --> 00:13:01.988
Well. we need to
discuss that with him.

296
00:13:02.172 --> 00:13:03.739
Flag officer on deck!

297
00:13:06.307 --> 00:13:07.787
As you were.

298
00:13:07.961 --> 00:13:09.527
Detectives. And...

299
00:13:09.745 --> 00:13:11.834
This is Lieutenant Brady.

300
00:13:12.052 --> 00:13:13.226
Have you made an arrest?

301
00:13:13.227 --> 00:13:15.055
No. but we think we might be close.

302
00:13:15.272 --> 00:13:17.013
Could we have a word
with you in private?

303
00:13:17.231 --> 00:13:18.511
Anything you need to say to me.

304
00:13:18.667 --> 00:13:19.798
you can say in front of them.

305
00:13:19.799 --> 00:13:22.671
We don't keep secrets on this ship.

306
00:13:22.845 --> 00:13:24.978
Okay.

307
00:13:25.195 --> 00:13:26.893
We think you were taking bribes.

308
00:13:27.110 --> 00:13:30.113
We think you met with Wally Kane
to talk about Frank Mazzeo

309
00:13:30.251 --> 00:13:31.287
because you knew the Feds would...

310
00:13:31.288 --> 00:13:32.724
Get the hell out of here.

311
00:13:32.899 --> 00:13:35.162
Sorry. that's not how this works.

312
00:13:35.379 --> 00:13:36.379
Now!

313
00:13:36.511 --> 00:13:37.947
What is this?

314
00:13:38.165 --> 00:13:40.080
This is a United States Navy vessel.

315
00:13:40.297 --> 00:13:42.038
a protected federal enclave

316
00:13:42.256 --> 00:13:44.649
under maritime and territorial
jurisdiction law.

317
00:13:44.824 --> 00:13:48.305
No one comes aboard
without my express permission.

318
00:13:48.523 --> 00:13:51.743
<i>[TENSE MUSIC]</i>

319
00:13:51.918 --> 00:13:58.489
<i>♪ ♪</i>

320
00:14:01.579 --> 00:14:03.364
Where's my evidence?

321
00:14:03.581 --> 00:14:05.713
We've got 17 cash deposits
made to Admiral Garvey's

322
00:14:05.714 --> 00:14:07.106
account over four months.

323
00:14:07.107 --> 00:14:10.153
All just less than $10.000
to avoid detection.

324
00:14:10.371 --> 00:14:11.371
Okay. but we need more.

325
00:14:11.546 --> 00:14:13.286
I got some video.

326
00:14:13.287 --> 00:14:15.724
Haven Avenue. a quarter mile
from the murder scene.

327
00:14:15.898 --> 00:14:18.814
six minutes after the 911 call.

328
00:14:18.988 --> 00:14:20.903
And it looks like Garvey.

329
00:14:21.121 --> 00:14:23.384
Yeah. that's that scarf
from the walkway video.

330
00:14:23.601 --> 00:14:25.342
Now. I couldn't get
a hit on facial rec.

331
00:14:25.560 --> 00:14:30.391
but he stops and talks to this
guy who's in uniform. a sailor.

332
00:14:30.608 --> 00:14:32.175
And we can see his face clear as day.

333
00:14:32.393 --> 00:14:35.309
And every member of the military
is in facial rec.

334
00:14:35.526 --> 00:14:37.180
Great. Track him down.

335
00:14:38.921 --> 00:14:41.184
You bet. That's me.

336
00:14:41.402 --> 00:14:43.926
You're positive you were
talking to Admiral Garvey?

337
00:14:44.144 --> 00:14:45.492
Are you kidding?

338
00:14:45.493 --> 00:14:48.190
To guys like us.
Admiral Garvey is a celebrity.

339
00:14:48.191 --> 00:14:50.498
I never even talked to him before.

340
00:14:50.715 --> 00:14:52.152
I wasn't gonna miss my chance.

341
00:14:52.369 --> 00:14:56.591
How did he seem
when you talked to him?

342
00:14:56.808 --> 00:14:59.898
A little shaken up. to be honest.

343
00:14:59.899 --> 00:15:03.685
Wasn't interested in a long
conversation. that's for sure.

344
00:15:03.903 --> 00:15:06.644
<i>[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC]</i>

345
00:15:06.862 --> 00:15:12.041
<i>♪ ♪</i>

346
00:15:12.259 --> 00:15:15.044
State your business.

347
00:15:15.262 --> 00:15:16.566
Don't bother.

348
00:15:16.567 --> 00:15:19.179
Pursuant to MRE 315.
NCIS has determined

349
00:15:19.396 --> 00:15:21.311
that probable cause exists
for these authorities

350
00:15:21.529 --> 00:15:23.270
to conduct a search of this vessel.

351
00:15:25.185 --> 00:15:26.576
This is a legal order.

352
00:15:26.577 --> 00:15:29.015
All hands will cooperate
and will not interfere.

353
00:15:29.232 --> 00:15:35.456
<i>♪ ♪</i>

354
00:15:36.805 --> 00:15:37.980
Shoot me.

355
00:15:53.430 --> 00:15:55.171
You wanna tell me
just what the hell it is

356
00:15:55.209 --> 00:15:58.392
you're trying to accomplish?

357
00:15:58.609 --> 00:16:00.960
I can read. This is goddamn outrageous.

358
00:16:01.134 --> 00:16:02.700
The law?

359
00:16:02.918 --> 00:16:04.572
Yeah. it's wild stuff.

360
00:16:04.789 --> 00:16:05.965
Lou.

361
00:16:10.230 --> 00:16:11.231
So?

362
00:16:11.448 --> 00:16:14.451
So...

363
00:16:14.669 --> 00:16:16.714
this is you

364
00:16:16.932 --> 00:16:19.041
wearing that scarf and pushing
your friend to his death.

365
00:16:19.065 --> 00:16:22.242
Can you turn around. Admiral?

366
00:16:22.459 --> 00:16:25.113
Place your hands behind
your back. please. sir.

367
00:16:25.114 --> 00:16:27.334
Rusten Garvey. you're under arrest

368
00:16:27.551 --> 00:16:30.032
for the murder
of Vice Admiral Wally Kane.

369
00:16:30.250 --> 00:16:31.686
<i>♪ ♪</i>

370
00:16:31.903 --> 00:16:35.995
[SOLDIERS SHOUTING]

371
00:16:36.212 --> 00:16:38.649
Take off my handcuffs
so I can return their salute.

372
00:16:38.867 --> 00:16:41.304
Enough theatrics. Let's go.

373
00:16:41.522 --> 00:16:43.480
I will be back on this deck!

374
00:16:45.569 --> 00:16:48.224
And you are gonna regret this.

375
00:16:53.981 --> 00:16:56.537
Okay. we'll talk soon.

376
00:16:56.547 --> 00:17:00.334
Are you really doing this?

377
00:17:00.551 --> 00:17:02.336
How's it going. Jack?

378
00:17:02.553 --> 00:17:03.966
I can't believe you're out and about.

379
00:17:03.990 --> 00:17:06.166
seeing how dangerous
this city is and all.

380
00:17:06.383 --> 00:17:09.386
Admiral Garvey
is a legend. a war hero.

381
00:17:09.604 --> 00:17:12.085
and you're gonna put him
on trial for murder?

382
00:17:12.302 --> 00:17:14.522
The evidence against him
is significant.

383
00:17:14.739 --> 00:17:16.219
It doesn't look like that to me.

384
00:17:16.437 --> 00:17:17.873
or the people I work with.

385
00:17:18.091 --> 00:17:19.920
He's set to be the next
Secretary of Defense.

386
00:17:19.946 --> 00:17:20.979
for God's sake.

387
00:17:21.004 --> 00:17:23.224
Irrelevant.

388
00:17:23.574 --> 00:17:25.838
To charge Garvey with murder

389
00:17:26.055 --> 00:17:29.537
is a slap in the face to a lot
of very important people. Nick.

390
00:17:29.754 --> 00:17:31.713
Not if he actually did it.

391
00:17:35.499 --> 00:17:36.804
[CAMERA SHUTTERS CLICKING]

392
00:17:36.805 --> 00:17:38.807
The People's case
is strong. Your Honor.

393
00:17:38.981 --> 00:17:41.069
We have video of the admiral
at the crime scene.

394
00:17:41.070 --> 00:17:42.550
And we believe the defendant presents

395
00:17:42.767 --> 00:17:44.421
a significant flight risk.

396
00:17:44.639 --> 00:17:46.815
He is an admiral in the
U.S. Navy. and if released.

397
00:17:46.989 --> 00:17:48.860
he will retake the helm
of his naval fleet

398
00:17:48.861 --> 00:17:50.688
and set sail for the Middle East.

399
00:17:50.863 --> 00:17:52.473
Mr. Banks.

400
00:17:52.690 --> 00:17:54.779
We plead not guilty and look forward

401
00:17:54.954 --> 00:17:57.217
to clearing
Admiral Garvey's reputation.

402
00:17:57.434 --> 00:17:59.828
As for bail.

403
00:18:00.002 --> 00:18:04.006
this man has served our nation
for three decades.

404
00:18:04.224 --> 00:18:05.660
We request reasonable bail.

405
00:18:05.878 --> 00:18:07.053
This is a murder case.

406
00:18:07.270 --> 00:18:08.837
Defendant is hereby remanded.

407
00:18:09.011 --> 00:18:11.099
Your Honor. this is
a political witch hunt.

408
00:18:11.100 --> 00:18:13.755
You can't penalize the defendant
for the DA's office...

409
00:18:13.929 --> 00:18:15.322
Watch it. Mr. Banks.

410
00:18:15.539 --> 00:18:17.541
- Next case.
- [GAVEL BANGS]

411
00:18:20.631 --> 00:18:23.069
We're challenging your video evidence.

412
00:18:30.293 --> 00:18:33.078
Judge Sullivan.
the video the People claim

413
00:18:33.079 --> 00:18:35.124
places my client at the crime scene

414
00:18:35.342 --> 00:18:36.952
was obtained from a bodega.

415
00:18:37.170 --> 00:18:40.173
It employed
extremely dated technology.

416
00:18:40.390 --> 00:18:43.828
This is an analog DVR-based system.

417
00:18:44.003 --> 00:18:46.048
first generation
of black box recorders.

418
00:18:46.266 --> 00:18:49.008
Back then. storage was at a premium.

419
00:18:49.225 --> 00:18:51.619
They saved space by using compression.

420
00:18:51.836 --> 00:18:53.621
When the storage is nearly full.

421
00:18:53.838 --> 00:18:55.710
which it always is
at this little shop.

422
00:18:55.928 --> 00:19:00.062
the frames per second rate
drops to 10 per minute.

423
00:19:00.280 --> 00:19:02.107
This is not reliable evidence.

424
00:19:02.108 --> 00:19:03.848
What say you?

425
00:19:04.023 --> 00:19:06.503
Your Honor. the law does not
require perfect technology.

426
00:19:06.721 --> 00:19:09.245
It requires reliable
authentication and relevance.

427
00:19:09.463 --> 00:19:10.550
and we have both.

428
00:19:10.551 --> 00:19:12.118
Now. yes. the system is older.

429
00:19:12.335 --> 00:19:14.685
but it doesn't mean that
these images are unreliable.

430
00:19:14.903 --> 00:19:17.253
I'm worried that the jury
might give undue weight

431
00:19:17.471 --> 00:19:19.821
to what appears to be
visual confirmation.

432
00:19:19.995 --> 00:19:21.431
But it is visual confirmation.

433
00:19:21.649 --> 00:19:23.912
Clearly with
demonstrable deficiencies.

434
00:19:24.086 --> 00:19:25.870
The video is out.

435
00:19:26.045 --> 00:19:27.568
Your Honor. this is...

436
00:19:27.785 --> 00:19:30.310
And that's the end of
the conversation. Mr. Price.

437
00:19:33.226 --> 00:19:35.445
Can we win without the video?

438
00:19:35.663 --> 00:19:37.404
Yes. the evidence is strong.

439
00:19:37.621 --> 00:19:39.100
Motive?

440
00:19:39.101 --> 00:19:41.021
Admiral Garvey was trying
to cover his own ass.

441
00:19:41.103 --> 00:19:42.583
What does that mean?

442
00:19:42.800 --> 00:19:45.978
Wally Kane knew that
Mazzeo was coming for him.

443
00:19:46.152 --> 00:19:47.587
that he was wearing a wire.

444
00:19:47.588 --> 00:19:49.546
So he called Garvey.
told him what was going on.

445
00:19:49.764 --> 00:19:52.985
They met up. presumably to talk
about the bind they were in.

446
00:19:53.159 --> 00:19:56.336
And Garvey got upset
and pushed Kane to his death.

447
00:19:56.553 --> 00:19:58.119
Something like that.

448
00:19:58.120 --> 00:19:59.663
Do the phone records and
cell data support all that?

449
00:19:59.687 --> 00:20:00.687
Yes.

450
00:20:00.731 --> 00:20:02.733
Okay. good.

451
00:20:02.951 --> 00:20:05.693
So we're still on solid ground.

452
00:20:05.910 --> 00:20:07.563
We are. yeah.

453
00:20:07.564 --> 00:20:12.178
But this whole video thing.
it was a pretty routine matter.

454
00:20:12.395 --> 00:20:14.199
I mean. we're talking
about surveillance video.

455
00:20:14.223 --> 00:20:16.138
It's the foundation
of modern police work.

456
00:20:16.356 --> 00:20:17.661
And as a result.

457
00:20:17.879 --> 00:20:19.620
the foundation
of most criminal trials.

458
00:20:19.837 --> 00:20:22.362
So for Sullivan
to flat-out suppress it.

459
00:20:22.579 --> 00:20:24.059
based on the simplistic argument that

460
00:20:24.190 --> 00:20:27.367
Attorney Banks put forth. it...

461
00:20:27.584 --> 00:20:28.845
it's hard to fathom.

462
00:20:28.846 --> 00:20:31.588
Well. judges have a lot of discretion.

463
00:20:31.806 --> 00:20:34.156
And like you said. the
surveillance system's outdated.

464
00:20:34.374 --> 00:20:36.854
so let it go and move on
to jury selection.

465
00:20:37.029 --> 00:20:38.309
Build a case with what you have.

466
00:20:38.421 --> 00:20:39.769
not with what you wish you had.

467
00:20:39.770 --> 00:20:43.035
Just make sure you
put together a solid jury.

468
00:20:43.252 --> 00:20:44.949
and they're not paying
too much attention

469
00:20:45.124 --> 00:20:47.169
to all that fake news out there.

470
00:20:47.387 --> 00:20:48.823
Yeah.

471
00:20:49.041 --> 00:20:51.695
I came across this little gem
a few hours ago.

472
00:20:51.913 --> 00:20:53.262
Thought you might appreciate it.

473
00:20:53.480 --> 00:20:55.395
Oh. God.

474
00:20:55.612 --> 00:20:57.962
Doesn't stop. does it?

475
00:21:01.053 --> 00:21:05.579
In our system of justice. a
defendant is presumed innocent.

476
00:21:05.796 --> 00:21:08.103
And that doesn't change
unless and until the People...

477
00:21:08.321 --> 00:21:10.279
that is myself and Ms. Maroun...

478
00:21:10.497 --> 00:21:13.978
prove our case
beyond a reasonable doubt.

479
00:21:14.153 --> 00:21:17.069
If we don't do that.
the law requires you

480
00:21:17.243 --> 00:21:20.072
to return a verdict of not guilty.

481
00:21:20.289 --> 00:21:23.379
So is there anybody here

482
00:21:23.597 --> 00:21:27.862
who feels that if a person
has been charged with a crime.

483
00:21:28.080 --> 00:21:30.256
they probably did something wrong?

484
00:21:32.345 --> 00:21:33.520
Very good.

485
00:21:33.737 --> 00:21:36.262
A-plus so far in civics.

486
00:21:36.479 --> 00:21:39.700
Another issue that we run into
is media coverage.

487
00:21:39.917 --> 00:21:41.919
Information is everywhere.
in the newspapers.

488
00:21:42.094 --> 00:21:43.617
our phones. social media.

489
00:21:43.834 --> 00:21:46.968
This case has garnered some publicity.

490
00:21:47.142 --> 00:21:52.060
Has anyone here read or heard
anything about this case?

491
00:21:52.234 --> 00:21:53.931
It's perfectly understandable.

492
00:21:54.106 --> 00:21:58.197
Juror 211. could you describe
what you've read or heard?

493
00:21:58.414 --> 00:22:01.069
This thing's been all over
the talk shows and stuff.

494
00:22:01.243 --> 00:22:02.984
My understanding is that the cops

495
00:22:03.158 --> 00:22:05.639
might have arrested the wrong guy.

496
00:22:05.856 --> 00:22:07.031
Goodness.

497
00:22:07.206 --> 00:22:09.556
Anyone else heard anything like that?

498
00:22:09.773 --> 00:22:10.773
Yeah. juror 214.

499
00:22:10.774 --> 00:22:12.036
Yeah. I heard the same stuff.

500
00:22:12.211 --> 00:22:13.821
Like. this whole thing is political.

501
00:22:14.038 --> 00:22:15.431
- A witch hunt.
- Right.

502
00:22:15.649 --> 00:22:17.477
- That's the word they used.
- Thank you.

503
00:22:17.694 --> 00:22:21.829
Your Honor. the People move to
excuse jurors 211. 214. and 216

504
00:22:22.046 --> 00:22:23.570
and thank them for their service.

505
00:22:23.787 --> 00:22:25.311
Approach.

506
00:22:29.141 --> 00:22:32.056
<i>[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC]</i>

507
00:22:32.231 --> 00:22:34.711
<i>♪ ♪</i>

508
00:22:34.929 --> 00:22:38.150
Mr. Price. Admiral Garvey
is a Southern white male.

509
00:22:38.324 --> 00:22:39.977
Uh. yes. correct.

510
00:22:40.152 --> 00:22:43.067
Well. you moved to excuse
three white men from this jury.

511
00:22:43.242 --> 00:22:44.828
I'm sorry. Your Honor.
I'm not following.

512
00:22:44.852 --> 00:22:46.419
As a matter of integrity. it's my job

513
00:22:46.636 --> 00:22:47.985
to guard against any impression

514
00:22:48.160 --> 00:22:50.945
that we might be stacking the jury.

515
00:22:51.163 --> 00:22:54.340
Batson tells us that these
strikes could be viewed

516
00:22:54.557 --> 00:22:57.430
as eliminating white men
in favor of minorities

517
00:22:57.647 --> 00:23:01.782
less inclined to sympathize
with the defendant.

518
00:23:01.999 --> 00:23:03.499
Your Honor. I am not moving to strike

519
00:23:03.523 --> 00:23:05.264
because they are white men.

520
00:23:05.481 --> 00:23:07.657
I'm moving to strike
because they acknowledged

521
00:23:07.875 --> 00:23:10.878
suggesting literal fake news
about this case.

522
00:23:12.401 --> 00:23:14.490
Help us out here. fellas.

523
00:23:14.708 --> 00:23:17.885
Could you still be objective
about this case.

524
00:23:18.102 --> 00:23:21.193
despite what you might
have heard on the news?

525
00:23:21.410 --> 00:23:22.976
Yeah. sure.

526
00:23:22.977 --> 00:23:25.240
You didn't walk in here today
with your mind made up

527
00:23:25.458 --> 00:23:29.200
regarding this man's
guilt or innocence?

528
00:23:29.201 --> 00:23:31.290
I don't guess so.

529
00:23:31.507 --> 00:23:32.855
There you have it.

530
00:23:32.856 --> 00:23:35.207
Your Honor. we're not
impugning the character

531
00:23:35.381 --> 00:23:37.905
of these jurors.
but there's no question

532
00:23:38.122 --> 00:23:39.776
that they've been exposed to material

533
00:23:39.994 --> 00:23:42.214
that would never be admissible
in this courtroom.

534
00:23:42.431 --> 00:23:44.564
This creates an unacceptable
risk of prejudice.

535
00:23:44.781 --> 00:23:46.479
Trial by jury does not require us

536
00:23:46.696 --> 00:23:51.092
to seek jurors who have lived
in isolation in this world.

537
00:23:51.266 --> 00:23:54.400
Motion to strike these men is denied.

538
00:23:54.617 --> 00:23:58.142
<i>♪ ♪</i>

539
00:24:03.887 --> 00:24:05.888
These are two of the most aggressive

540
00:24:05.889 --> 00:24:07.804
pro-defense rulings I've ever seen.

541
00:24:08.022 --> 00:24:10.198
Video compression? Nonsense.

542
00:24:10.372 --> 00:24:12.983
And this Batson ruling... it's absurd.

543
00:24:13.201 --> 00:24:15.595
Batson was designed
to protect Black defendants

544
00:24:15.812 --> 00:24:18.467
who used to get railroaded
by all-white juries.

545
00:24:18.685 --> 00:24:19.816
not powerful white men.

546
00:24:20.034 --> 00:24:22.689
It makes no sense...

547
00:24:22.906 --> 00:24:26.345
unless. of course.
that is the whole point.

548
00:24:26.562 --> 00:24:28.303
- Meaning what?
- Meaning.

549
00:24:28.521 --> 00:24:31.437
unless Sullivan knows
what he's doing makes no sense.

550
00:24:31.654 --> 00:24:33.265
Wait. are you suggesting...

551
00:24:33.439 --> 00:24:35.963
I can't prove that
he is in Garvey's pocket.

552
00:24:36.180 --> 00:24:39.706
but it definitely feels that way.

553
00:24:39.923 --> 00:24:43.144
Are you seriously accusing
Sullivan of being corrupt?

554
00:24:43.318 --> 00:24:44.841
He's been on the bench for 20 years.

555
00:24:45.059 --> 00:24:46.321
He was a prosecutor for 15.

556
00:24:46.539 --> 00:24:48.410
He started out right here
in this office.

557
00:24:48.628 --> 00:24:50.107
He held your job for. like. five.

558
00:24:50.282 --> 00:24:51.412
Exactly.

559
00:24:51.413 --> 00:24:52.457
That is why this is so concerning.

560
00:24:52.458 --> 00:24:54.286
because he knows better.

561
00:24:54.460 --> 00:24:56.288
I think he should recuse himself.

562
00:24:56.462 --> 00:24:58.028
On what grounds?

563
00:24:58.246 --> 00:25:00.086
Does he know the defendant.
his family members?

564
00:25:00.248 --> 00:25:01.379
Not to my knowledge.

565
00:25:01.380 --> 00:25:02.467
Does he have any special relationship

566
00:25:02.468 --> 00:25:03.904
with Attorney Banks. with the Navy?

567
00:25:04.121 --> 00:25:05.514
Not to my knowledge.

568
00:25:05.732 --> 00:25:07.057
So what. are you gonna
ask him to step aside

569
00:25:07.081 --> 00:25:08.952
'cause you think he's a prick?

570
00:25:09.170 --> 00:25:11.607
For starters. he's gonna
tell you to go to hell.

571
00:25:11.825 --> 00:25:14.218
And then he's really gonna jam you.

572
00:25:14.243 --> 00:25:16.917
Going to war with a judge
is bad business. Nolan.

573
00:25:17.134 --> 00:25:20.050
[LAUGHS] So you want me to
pretend this isn't happening?

574
00:25:20.268 --> 00:25:21.941
I want you to pretend
that he doesn't matter

575
00:25:21.965 --> 00:25:23.445
as much as you think he does.

576
00:25:23.663 --> 00:25:25.882
The jury makes the decision. not him.

577
00:25:26.100 --> 00:25:29.277
<i>[TENSE MUSIC]</i>

578
00:25:29.451 --> 00:25:34.543
<i>♪ ♪</i>

579
00:25:34.761 --> 00:25:36.937
Kenneth.

580
00:25:37.154 --> 00:25:39.505
- Nick.
- Hey.

581
00:25:39.722 --> 00:25:41.352
You know. as you might expect.
I've been following

582
00:25:41.376 --> 00:25:42.856
this Garvey case pretty closely.

583
00:25:43.073 --> 00:25:44.161
Is that right?

584
00:25:44.336 --> 00:25:46.729
Yeah. a lot of eyes on this one.

585
00:25:46.947 --> 00:25:50.342
I'm guessing you're pleased with that.

586
00:25:50.516 --> 00:25:52.866
Is that what this is all about?

587
00:25:53.083 --> 00:25:56.260
Me getting the nod for the
DA position instead of you?

588
00:25:56.435 --> 00:25:58.088
I know you wanted it.

589
00:25:58.306 --> 00:26:00.700
Your people weren't
very subtle about it.

590
00:26:00.917 --> 00:26:03.180
I have no idea
what you're talking about.

591
00:26:03.355 --> 00:26:06.836
Well. let me be a little more direct.

592
00:26:07.054 --> 00:26:09.448
You've made two
questionable legal rulings.

593
00:26:09.665 --> 00:26:11.232
and I'm trying to understand why.

594
00:26:11.406 --> 00:26:14.322
Every decision I make
is based on the law.

595
00:26:14.496 --> 00:26:15.757
I sure hope so.

596
00:26:15.758 --> 00:26:17.456
That's the whole point
of this. isn't it?

597
00:26:17.673 --> 00:26:20.197
To follow the law?

598
00:26:20.372 --> 00:26:22.809
To get justice?

599
00:26:23.026 --> 00:26:25.226
I'm gonna give you the benefit
of the doubt on this one.

600
00:26:25.333 --> 00:26:26.453
Kenneth. for the time being.

601
00:26:26.639 --> 00:26:28.641
Is that a threat?

602
00:26:28.858 --> 00:26:31.339
No. it's a compliment.

603
00:26:31.513 --> 00:26:33.950
I have too much respect
for you and your career

604
00:26:34.168 --> 00:26:36.736
to ask for a recusal.

605
00:26:36.953 --> 00:26:39.826
Ask me. you're the one
acting unethically.

606
00:26:40.043 --> 00:26:41.348
Excuse me?

607
00:26:41.349 --> 00:26:44.787
Reaching out to me
on an ex parte basis.

608
00:26:45.005 --> 00:26:47.355
trying to influence a case.

609
00:26:47.529 --> 00:26:49.444
No!

610
00:26:49.662 --> 00:26:52.273
We're just two people
trying to do the right thing

611
00:26:52.447 --> 00:26:53.887
who happened to bump into each other

612
00:26:53.970 --> 00:26:56.408
outside the courthouse.

613
00:26:56.625 --> 00:26:58.888
Have a nice evening.

614
00:27:01.978 --> 00:27:05.982
Vice Admiral Wallace Kane was a hero.

615
00:27:06.200 --> 00:27:09.551
But like all of us.

616
00:27:09.769 --> 00:27:12.293
he was far from perfect.

617
00:27:12.467 --> 00:27:14.469
Two years ago. the FBI discovered

618
00:27:14.687 --> 00:27:18.299
that a man named Frank Mazzeo
was bribing naval officers

619
00:27:18.473 --> 00:27:20.780
to dock their vessels at his slips.

620
00:27:20.997 --> 00:27:23.609
The FBI asked Mr. Mazzeo to cooperate

621
00:27:23.826 --> 00:27:26.916
to implicate the men
that he was paying off.

622
00:27:27.134 --> 00:27:31.399
Vice Admiral Kane
was one of those men.

623
00:27:31.573 --> 00:27:34.575
On the night of the murder.
Mr. Mazzeo met with Kane.

624
00:27:34.576 --> 00:27:37.274
wearing a wire.
hoping to incriminate him.

625
00:27:37.449 --> 00:27:41.235
But Wally Kane was nobody's fool.

626
00:27:41.453 --> 00:27:45.587
He clammed up. he rushed out.
and the first thing he did

627
00:27:45.805 --> 00:27:50.157
was to call his partner
in crime. the defendant.

628
00:27:51.680 --> 00:27:54.248
It was clear to Admiral Garvey
that their secrets

629
00:27:54.466 --> 00:27:56.511
might be exposed. that this whole mess

630
00:27:56.729 --> 00:27:59.645
had to be put to bed.
loose ends tied up.

631
00:27:59.862 --> 00:28:02.822
So he pushed Wally Kane
off the side of a walkway

632
00:28:03.039 --> 00:28:06.826
and watched him fall to his death.

633
00:28:07.043 --> 00:28:09.611
This is the story of two good men.

634
00:28:09.829 --> 00:28:13.920
two brave men doing bad things.

635
00:28:14.137 --> 00:28:19.099
One of those men is now dead.
and the other is the killer.

636
00:28:23.320 --> 00:28:26.236
As Mr. Price just stated.

637
00:28:26.454 --> 00:28:30.806
Admiral Garvey is a brave man.

638
00:28:31.024 --> 00:28:34.157
a hero of several wars.

639
00:28:34.375 --> 00:28:38.205
Admiral Garvey
did not kill Wally Kane.

640
00:28:38.422 --> 00:28:39.510
He loved Wally Kane.

641
00:28:39.511 --> 00:28:41.034
They were roommates at Annapolis.

642
00:28:41.251 --> 00:28:45.386
They worked together for 20 years.

643
00:28:45.560 --> 00:28:49.521
The sad truth here is...

644
00:28:49.738 --> 00:28:53.916
the NYPD and the
District Attorney's Office

645
00:28:54.134 --> 00:28:57.659
knew they were under
a political scrutiny.

646
00:28:57.877 --> 00:29:01.663
that the world was watching
and judging them

647
00:29:01.881 --> 00:29:03.883
for allowing something like this

648
00:29:04.100 --> 00:29:05.798
to happen in the first place.

649
00:29:06.015 --> 00:29:08.235
- Objection.
- Overruled.

650
00:29:08.452 --> 00:29:10.149
And the cherry on top. of course.

651
00:29:10.150 --> 00:29:14.937
was the chance to embarrass the
federal government. the Navy.

652
00:29:15.155 --> 00:29:18.462
As this trial moves forward.

653
00:29:18.637 --> 00:29:21.074
please pay attention

654
00:29:21.291 --> 00:29:24.730
to the lack of specific evidence

655
00:29:24.947 --> 00:29:27.080
and the far-fetched narrative

656
00:29:27.297 --> 00:29:29.952
the prosecution
is attempting to craft.

657
00:29:30.170 --> 00:29:33.216
If you do that. you will
come to two conclusions...

658
00:29:33.434 --> 00:29:36.872
one. that Admiral Garvey
did not kill Wally Kane.

659
00:29:37.090 --> 00:29:39.745
and two. the DA's office

660
00:29:39.962 --> 00:29:44.619
cares more about politics
than the law.

661
00:29:44.837 --> 00:29:49.711
Thank you for your time.
for your service.

662
00:29:49.929 --> 00:29:51.234
and your fairness.

663
00:29:51.452 --> 00:29:52.627
We will break for lunch.

664
00:29:52.845 --> 00:29:54.934
All parties back here in 90 minutes.

665
00:29:55.151 --> 00:29:57.893
[GAVEL BANGS]

666
00:29:58.111 --> 00:29:59.373
[HANDCUFFS CLICKING]

667
00:29:59.591 --> 00:30:02.202
- Call Mazzeo.
- Now?

668
00:30:02.419 --> 00:30:04.180
Yeah. we're gonna
kick this thing off in style.

669
00:30:04.204 --> 00:30:05.640
make it clear right from the start

670
00:30:05.858 --> 00:30:07.990
that despite the fancy title
and uniform.

671
00:30:08.208 --> 00:30:11.385
Garvey is not
a knight in shining armor.

672
00:30:12.647 --> 00:30:14.867
Navy ships are big.

673
00:30:15.084 --> 00:30:18.522
They need a lot of dock space.
especially during Fleet Week.

674
00:30:18.697 --> 00:30:20.742
when a bunch need to park
at the same time.

675
00:30:20.960 --> 00:30:25.312
So you know. I would incentivize

676
00:30:25.529 --> 00:30:28.968
certain people to use my ports
here in New York.

677
00:30:29.185 --> 00:30:30.839
New Orleans. San Diego.

678
00:30:31.057 --> 00:30:33.102
And by "incentivize."
you mean paying them cash?

679
00:30:33.320 --> 00:30:34.581
Yeah.

680
00:30:34.582 --> 00:30:36.932
And Wally Kane was
one of those people?

681
00:30:37.150 --> 00:30:38.280
Yes.

682
00:30:38.281 --> 00:30:39.563
When was the last time you saw him?

683
00:30:39.587 --> 00:30:40.893
The night he was killed.

684
00:30:41.110 --> 00:30:42.938
We met for a drink
at a bar on 18th Street.

685
00:30:43.156 --> 00:30:44.810
What was your agenda that evening?

686
00:30:45.027 --> 00:30:48.117
To get Wally to say something stupid.

687
00:30:48.335 --> 00:30:50.119
Can you elaborate?

688
00:30:50.337 --> 00:30:53.122
I was wearing a wire.
a listening device.

689
00:30:53.340 --> 00:30:54.796
I was trying to get him to acknowledge

690
00:30:54.820 --> 00:30:56.952
that we were doing business together.

691
00:30:57.170 --> 00:31:00.173
and he was being paid.

692
00:31:00.390 --> 00:31:01.653
He didn't... he didn't bite.

693
00:31:01.827 --> 00:31:03.655
You ever do business
with the defendant?

694
00:31:03.872 --> 00:31:06.701
No. not directly. but Wally said

695
00:31:06.919 --> 00:31:08.616
he shared the bribes with his boss.

696
00:31:08.790 --> 00:31:11.358
- Objection... hearsay.
- Sustained.

697
00:31:11.575 --> 00:31:15.014
Nothing further.

698
00:31:15.231 --> 00:31:18.365
This... this bribery scheme
was your idea?

699
00:31:18.582 --> 00:31:20.323
Correct.

700
00:31:20.541 --> 00:31:22.737
And you obviously knew what
you were doing was illegal.

701
00:31:22.761 --> 00:31:24.066
Correct.

702
00:31:24.284 --> 00:31:27.679
So breaking the law
doesn't bother you?

703
00:31:27.853 --> 00:31:29.506
No. it bothered me.

704
00:31:29.681 --> 00:31:31.421
It bothered me.

705
00:31:31.639 --> 00:31:33.815
Just not enough. I suppose.

706
00:31:34.033 --> 00:31:36.339
[CHUCKLES] Was that meant to be funny?

707
00:31:36.557 --> 00:31:38.385
No. just honest.

708
00:31:38.602 --> 00:31:40.953
So you're honest
about being a criminal.

709
00:31:41.170 --> 00:31:45.435
about your willingness to
deceive people. skirt the law.

710
00:31:45.653 --> 00:31:48.090
That's one way to put it.

711
00:31:48.308 --> 00:31:52.399
Isn't it also true
that you were arrested

712
00:31:52.616 --> 00:31:55.010
nine years ago for domestic assault?

713
00:31:55.228 --> 00:31:56.707
Objection.

714
00:31:56.708 --> 00:31:58.076
It goes to the witness's
credibility. Your Honor.

715
00:31:58.100 --> 00:31:59.295
Your Honor. this is outrageous.

716
00:31:59.319 --> 00:32:00.319
Relax.

717
00:32:00.494 --> 00:32:02.235
No need for hyperbole.

718
00:32:02.452 --> 00:32:04.716
Let's discuss this in chambers.
[GAVEL BANGS]

719
00:32:04.890 --> 00:32:07.153
Court is adjourned.

720
00:32:07.370 --> 00:32:09.938
<i>[TENSE MUSIC]</i>

721
00:32:10.156 --> 00:32:12.332
Yeah. Mazzeo was arrested
but never convicted.

722
00:32:12.549 --> 00:32:13.985
Hell. he wasn't even charged.

723
00:32:13.986 --> 00:32:16.249
But even if he had been
and was then convicted.

724
00:32:16.466 --> 00:32:18.033
it still isn't admissible.

725
00:32:18.251 --> 00:32:20.209
It has absolutely nothing to do

726
00:32:20.427 --> 00:32:21.907
with his propensity for truthfulness.

727
00:32:21.950 --> 00:32:23.952
- I don't know about that.
- Excuse me?

728
00:32:24.170 --> 00:32:26.563
People who commit crimes
are inherently

729
00:32:26.738 --> 00:32:28.435
less believable than people who don't.

730
00:32:28.652 --> 00:32:30.263
That's not...

731
00:32:32.918 --> 00:32:35.659
All right. okay.

732
00:32:35.834 --> 00:32:37.714
All right. let's... let's say
that you're right.

733
00:32:37.836 --> 00:32:40.055
But the defense has
already made that point.

734
00:32:40.273 --> 00:32:42.014
And they already established
that the FBI

735
00:32:42.231 --> 00:32:43.971
was investigating Mazzeo for bribery

736
00:32:43.972 --> 00:32:46.492
and that they gave him immunity
in exchange for his cooperation.

737
00:32:46.627 --> 00:32:47.759
And that all makes sense.

738
00:32:47.976 --> 00:32:49.499
That is directly related to this case

739
00:32:49.717 --> 00:32:51.239
and to the defendant's motive.

740
00:32:51.240 --> 00:32:54.026
But this alleged domestic
assault from nine years ago

741
00:32:54.243 --> 00:32:57.769
has absolutely nothing to do
with whether or not

742
00:32:57.986 --> 00:32:59.379
Admiral Garvey killed Wally Kane.

743
00:32:59.596 --> 00:33:00.727
Sure. it does.

744
00:33:00.728 --> 00:33:04.905
It speaks to who this man is in full.

745
00:33:04.906 --> 00:33:06.385
I agree.

746
00:33:06.386 --> 00:33:09.171
The jury has a right to know
that the man accusing

747
00:33:09.389 --> 00:33:12.827
a war hero of fraud.
and. by implication. murder.

748
00:33:13.045 --> 00:33:17.049
is not only a career hustler.
but a wife beater.

749
00:33:17.266 --> 00:33:19.442
You may proceed.

750
00:33:19.660 --> 00:33:22.315
<i>[PENSIVE MUSIC]</i>

751
00:33:22.532 --> 00:33:26.144
<i>♪ ♪</i>

752
00:33:26.145 --> 00:33:28.582
I don't know what to say.

753
00:33:28.800 --> 00:33:31.150
other than this is
a highly unusual decision.

754
00:33:31.367 --> 00:33:32.607
No. it's more than that. Nick.

755
00:33:32.716 --> 00:33:35.937
He is jamming us at every turn.

756
00:33:36.155 --> 00:33:39.071
Can't be a coincidence.
It is not a coincidence.

757
00:33:39.288 --> 00:33:43.815
I know you don't wanna hear this
right now or accept it.

758
00:33:43.989 --> 00:33:45.817
but he is in Garvey's pocket.

759
00:33:45.991 --> 00:33:49.908
There is no other explanation.

760
00:33:50.125 --> 00:33:53.389
The question is. can we prove it?

761
00:33:53.607 --> 00:33:56.610
<i>♪ ♪</i>

762
00:34:02.921 --> 00:34:05.097
I'm not sure I understand
where you're coming from.

763
00:34:05.314 --> 00:34:08.142
I'm just trying to...

764
00:34:08.143 --> 00:34:12.887
this case has been unusual
in many ways.

765
00:34:13.105 --> 00:34:14.671
Oh. how so?

766
00:34:14.846 --> 00:34:18.241
There have been a series
of questionable rulings

767
00:34:18.266 --> 00:34:22.723
that I'd prefer not to bring
into the weeds on this.

768
00:34:22.897 --> 00:34:25.508
I appreciate that. I think.

769
00:34:25.726 --> 00:34:27.815
To put my paranoia to bed.

770
00:34:27.989 --> 00:34:30.731
I need to know how Sullivan
caught this case.

771
00:34:30.905 --> 00:34:32.472
You're the chief administrative judge.

772
00:34:32.689 --> 00:34:35.475
The docket flows through your office.

773
00:34:35.692 --> 00:34:40.132
Was this case assigned to
Sullivan. or did he ask for it?

774
00:34:40.349 --> 00:34:42.669
[SIGHS] Are you really saying
what I think you're saying?

775
00:34:42.874 --> 00:34:45.964
I don't know
what to tell you. Charles.

776
00:34:46.181 --> 00:34:47.879
other than I wouldn't be here

777
00:34:48.053 --> 00:34:49.793
if this weren't a serious matter.

778
00:34:49.968 --> 00:34:52.753
<i>[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC]</i>

779
00:34:52.927 --> 00:34:56.104
<i>♪ ♪</i>

780
00:34:56.322 --> 00:34:57.453
Off the record?

781
00:34:57.647 --> 00:34:59.577
Of course.

782
00:34:59.602 --> 00:35:02.260
Yeah. Sullivan asked for it...
claimed he had some expertise

783
00:35:02.284 --> 00:35:05.070
handling cases involving the military.

784
00:35:05.287 --> 00:35:09.291
<i>♪ ♪</i>

785
00:35:09.509 --> 00:35:12.686
I kept hoping I was wrong.
that I was overthinking it.

786
00:35:12.904 --> 00:35:15.907
but you bastards
are really doing this.

787
00:35:16.124 --> 00:35:18.344
You're really trying
to fix this damn thing.

788
00:35:21.434 --> 00:35:24.437
That's... that's a hell
of an accusation.

789
00:35:24.654 --> 00:35:27.092
Sullivan requested this case.

790
00:35:27.309 --> 00:35:30.269
He's now on the short list for
the Federal Court of Appeals.

791
00:35:30.486 --> 00:35:32.706
He's made pro-defense
ruling after ruling

792
00:35:32.924 --> 00:35:34.969
that made no sense. unless. of course.

793
00:35:35.187 --> 00:35:36.642
you look at them through
a different lens.

794
00:35:36.666 --> 00:35:38.320
and then they make
a whole lot of sense.

795
00:35:38.538 --> 00:35:40.932
Why are we really here. Nick?

796
00:35:41.149 --> 00:35:43.349
I guess I just wanted a chance
to look you in the face

797
00:35:43.456 --> 00:35:45.632
and say. I know.

798
00:35:45.849 --> 00:35:48.330
and that I'm coming for you
and Sullivan

799
00:35:48.548 --> 00:35:50.419
and everyone else involved
in this damn thing.

800
00:35:50.637 --> 00:35:52.291
That would be unwise.

801
00:35:52.508 --> 00:35:54.510
But I don't care.

802
00:35:54.728 --> 00:35:59.950
I am done with this nonsense.

803
00:35:59.951 --> 00:36:03.563
Does everything have to be
so damn political?

804
00:36:03.780 --> 00:36:05.869
Us vs. You?

805
00:36:06.044 --> 00:36:07.480
Can't it just be about the law?

806
00:36:07.697 --> 00:36:09.134
[SIGHS]

807
00:36:09.351 --> 00:36:11.178
Garvey was taking bribes.

808
00:36:11.179 --> 00:36:14.443
He was afraid he was gonna
get caught and he killed a guy.

809
00:36:14.661 --> 00:36:16.706
That's what happened.

810
00:36:16.924 --> 00:36:18.665
Does it really matter?

811
00:36:18.882 --> 00:36:20.232
What the hell does that mean?

812
00:36:20.449 --> 00:36:23.148
[SCOFFS]
It means we want what we want.

813
00:36:23.365 --> 00:36:27.282
And if I were you. I would
find a brilliant legal reason

814
00:36:27.500 --> 00:36:29.371
to give it to us. to dismiss the case.

815
00:36:29.589 --> 00:36:31.243
Win. win.

816
00:36:31.460 --> 00:36:33.810
We get the Secretary of Defense
we want.

817
00:36:33.985 --> 00:36:37.336
and you get to wrap yourself
in the Constitution

818
00:36:37.553 --> 00:36:40.774
and reassure the voters
that you are a noble prosecutor

819
00:36:40.992 --> 00:36:44.865
who would never convict someone
without sufficient evidence.

820
00:36:45.039 --> 00:36:46.519
Not gonna happen.

821
00:36:46.736 --> 00:36:49.652
Our case is still strong.

822
00:36:49.870 --> 00:36:51.915
despite your attempts to undermine it.

823
00:36:52.090 --> 00:36:55.615
<i>[TENSE MUSIC]</i>

824
00:36:55.832 --> 00:36:57.138
Oh.

825
00:36:57.356 --> 00:37:02.578
<i>♪ ♪</i>

826
00:37:02.796 --> 00:37:04.144
You were right. Nolan.

827
00:37:04.145 --> 00:37:06.017
You were right all along.

828
00:37:06.234 --> 00:37:07.801
I wish that weren't true.

829
00:37:08.019 --> 00:37:09.759
I'm gonna demand a mistrial.

830
00:37:09.977 --> 00:37:11.238
Really?

831
00:37:11.239 --> 00:37:12.457
And then I'm gonna
file criminal charges

832
00:37:12.458 --> 00:37:14.242
against Sullivan and everyone else

833
00:37:14.460 --> 00:37:16.027
involved in this damn conspiracy.

834
00:37:16.201 --> 00:37:18.071
I'm not so sure that's...

835
00:37:18.072 --> 00:37:19.987
What's the alternative?

836
00:37:20.161 --> 00:37:22.685
To stand by and let them make a
mockery of the judicial system?

837
00:37:22.903 --> 00:37:25.253
No. but you're the one who told me

838
00:37:25.471 --> 00:37:27.647
not to get emotional.
that attacking judges

839
00:37:27.864 --> 00:37:29.170
- is bad business...
- Stop.

840
00:37:29.388 --> 00:37:31.346
Just stop.

841
00:37:31.564 --> 00:37:34.393
I'm not here for conversation
or a lecture.

842
00:37:34.610 --> 00:37:37.178
Just send me the file.
I'll handle it from here.

843
00:37:37.396 --> 00:37:42.966
<i>♪ ♪</i>

844
00:37:43.141 --> 00:37:44.620
[DOORBELL CHIMES]

845
00:37:52.585 --> 00:37:54.065
Ah.

846
00:37:55.936 --> 00:37:57.807
Is this what I think it is?

847
00:38:01.637 --> 00:38:04.858
Well. I'm happy to talk.

848
00:38:05.076 --> 00:38:08.731
but we're feeling pretty good
about where we stand.

849
00:38:08.949 --> 00:38:10.951
Good enough to toss a coin?

850
00:38:11.125 --> 00:38:12.735
Heads. Garvey walks.

851
00:38:12.953 --> 00:38:15.608
Tails. he spends the rest
of his life in prison.

852
00:38:27.837 --> 00:38:30.405
Criminally negligent homicide?

853
00:38:30.623 --> 00:38:32.223
You really cut a deal
with Admiral Garvey

854
00:38:32.277 --> 00:38:34.105
without my consent?

855
00:38:39.893 --> 00:38:42.200
Yes. I did. given the facts.

856
00:38:42.417 --> 00:38:43.853
He'll be out in a year.

857
00:38:44.071 --> 00:38:45.463
Hell. they might even
suspend his sentence.

858
00:38:45.464 --> 00:38:47.944
Yeah. maybe.
but at least we got something.

859
00:38:48.119 --> 00:38:50.009
'Cause we didn't have the cards.
Nick. we just didn't.

860
00:38:50.033 --> 00:38:54.037
That is my decision. not yours.

861
00:38:54.212 --> 00:38:56.431
[SIGHS]

862
00:38:56.649 --> 00:38:58.520
I just couldn't stand there

863
00:38:58.738 --> 00:39:00.522
and watch you destroy your career.

864
00:39:00.740 --> 00:39:02.785
<i>[SOLEMN MUSIC]</i>

865
00:39:03.003 --> 00:39:05.788
You should worry about you.

866
00:39:06.006 --> 00:39:08.051
about your career.

867
00:39:08.226 --> 00:39:09.626
Well. that's what I'm doing. Nick.

868
00:39:09.792 --> 00:39:11.142
And how's that?

869
00:39:11.316 --> 00:39:13.274
You go after Sullivan.
you will get blown up.

870
00:39:13.492 --> 00:39:15.885
you'll lose the election.
and I will lose my job.

871
00:39:16.103 --> 00:39:17.713
And I like what I do.
and I'm good at it.

872
00:39:17.931 --> 00:39:19.976
So if it makes you feel any better.

873
00:39:20.151 --> 00:39:25.068
I did this for me. not you.

874
00:39:25.243 --> 00:39:26.635
It doesn't.

875
00:39:26.853 --> 00:39:31.553
<i>♪ ♪</i>

876
00:39:31.771 --> 00:39:35.253
Someone needs to hold the line.

877
00:39:35.470 --> 00:39:38.995
Why not us?

878
00:39:39.170 --> 00:39:41.998
Why not now?

879
00:39:42.173 --> 00:39:45.524
<i>♪ ♪</i>

880
00:39:45.741 --> 00:39:47.961
<i>This morning. Admiral Rusten Garvey</i>

881
00:39:48.179 --> 00:39:53.532
pleaded guilty to one count of
criminally negligent homicide.

882
00:39:53.749 --> 00:39:56.709
Based on the evidence
and the specific facts

883
00:39:56.734 --> 00:39:59.226
and circumstances of this case.

884
00:39:59.251 --> 00:40:04.151
we believe this is
a just result for all parties.

885
00:40:04.325 --> 00:40:09.112
In this country. we do not
prosecute to please a crowd.

886
00:40:09.287 --> 00:40:13.421
and we do not neglect
to prosecute to appease one.

887
00:40:13.639 --> 00:40:18.600
The courtroom is a place
where facts still matter.

888
00:40:18.818 --> 00:40:21.081
where evidence still matters.

889
00:40:21.255 --> 00:40:26.565
where the law quietly
and deliberately does its work.

890
00:40:26.782 --> 00:40:29.350
And we must fight as hard as we can

891
00:40:29.568 --> 00:40:32.092
to protect the sanctity
of this hallowed institution

892
00:40:32.266 --> 00:40:36.227
because if we don't. this whole thing.

893
00:40:36.444 --> 00:40:40.187
this grand experiment will crumble.

894
00:40:43.146 --> 00:40:46.498
When we feel ill... [SIGHS]

895
00:40:46.715 --> 00:40:50.458
When we feel that lies and injustice

896
00:40:50.676 --> 00:40:53.461
are beginning to invade
our collective well-being.

897
00:40:53.679 --> 00:40:58.292
law is the medicine
that can help us heal.

898
00:40:58.510 --> 00:41:02.587
<i>♪ ♪</i>

899
00:41:02.837 --> 00:41:08.338
sync & corrections <font color="#FF0000">awaqeded</font>
